04146nmm a2200601Ia 9780801467615DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1298400474  a97808014676157 a10.7591/97808014676152doi  a(DE-B1597)515850  a(OCoLC)827455689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHC800b.J47 201304a338.9672231 aJerven, Morten, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoor Numbers :bHow We Are Misled by African Development Statistics and What to Do about It /cMorten Jerven. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b12 tables, 2 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Political Economy0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the most urgent challenges in African economic development is to devise a strategy for improving statistical capacity. Reliable statistics, including estimates of economic growth rates and per-capita income, are basic to the operation of governments in developing countries and vital to nongovernmental organizations and other entities that provide financial aid to them. Rich countries and international financial institutions such as the World Bank allocate their development resources on the basis of such data. The paucity of accurate statistics is not merely a technical problem; it has a massive impact on the welfare of citizens in developing countries.Where do these statistics originate? How accurate are they? Poor Numbers is the first analysis of the production and use of African economic development statistics. Morten Jerven's research shows how the statistical capacities of sub-Saharan African economies have fallen into disarray. The numbers substantially misstate the actual state of affairs. As a result, scarce resources are misapplied. Development policy does not deliver the benefits expected. Policymakers' attempts to improve the lot of the citizenry are frustrated. Donors have no accurate sense of the impact of the aid they supply. Jerven's findings from sub-Saharan Africa have far-reaching implications for aid and development policy. As Jerven notes, the current catchphrase in the development community is "evidence-based policy," and scholars are applying increasingly sophisticated econometric methods—but no statistical techniques can substitute for partial and unreliable data.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic developmentzAfrica, Sub-SaharanvStatistics. 0aEconomic indicatorszAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aNational incomezAfrica, SouthernxAccounting. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.  aaftican economical development, african political economy, reliability of statistics, developing countries, development resources, world bank, statistical error.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146761540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801467615423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801467615/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles